2.2 Alternative-case release

The alternative scenario is considered to be defined by a release of ammonia that is more likely to occur than the worst-case scenario, and reaches an endpoint offsite.

The ?ALOHA Plan? scenario was used for this analysis, which assumes a release of ammonia through a 3/8-inch effective diameter hole in the largest vessel (i.e., 200 psig), releasing 62.3 pounds of ammonia per minute.  Using the specified meteorology contained in the ?ALOHA Plan?, the distance to the endpoint for the ?more likely? release scenario extends beyond the facility boundary.

The alternative release scenario is unlikely for the following reasons:

?Industrial standards were followed for the manufacture and quality control of these lines;
?The facility has a full alarm sprinkler system throughout the plant which is also heat activated;
?Ammonia detectors exist in the entire engine room, which would detect a leak quickly;
?The facility has a preventive maintenance program in place to maintain the ongoing integrity of the system; and
?The facility has a training program designed to ensure that the system is operated by qualified personnel.

